SH.ALC.PCAP.FE.LI-gq.def: Total alcohol per capita consumption is defined as the total (sum of recorded and unrecorded alcohol) amount of alcohol consumed per person (15 years of age or older) over a calendar year, in litres of pure alcohol, adjusted for tourist consumption.
SH.ALC.PCAP.FE.LI-gq.name: Total alcohol consumption per capita
SH.ALC.PCAP.FE.LI-gq.source: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository (http://apps.who.int/ghodata/).
SH.ALC.PCAP.FE.LI-gq.units: liters of pure alcohol, projected estimates, female 15+ years of age

SH.ALC.PCAP.LI-gq.def: Total alcohol per capita consumption is defined as the total (sum of recorded and unrecorded alcohol) amount of alcohol consumed per person (15 years of age or older) over a calendar year, in litres of pure alcohol, adjusted for tourist consumption.
SH.ALC.PCAP.LI-gq.name: Total alcohol consumption per capita
SH.ALC.PCAP.LI-gq.source: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository (http://apps.who.int/ghodata/).
SH.ALC.PCAP.LI-gq.dim: liters of pure alcohol, projected estimates, 15+ years of age
SH.ALC.PCAP.LI-gq.units: liters of pure alcohol, projected estimates, 15+ years of age

SH.ALC.PCAP.MA.LI-gq.def: Total alcohol per capita consumption is defined as the total (sum of recorded and unrecorded alcohol) amount of alcohol consumed per person (15 years of age or older) over a calendar year, in litres of pure alcohol, adjusted for tourist consumption.
SH.ALC.PCAP.MA.LI-gq.name: Total alcohol consumption per capita
SH.ALC.PCAP.MA.LI-gq.source: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository (http://apps.who.int/ghodata/).
SH.ALC.PCAP.MA.LI-gq.units: liters of pure alcohol, projected estimates, male 15+ years of age

SH.DTH.COMM.ZS-gq.def: Cause of death refers to the share of all deaths for all ages by underlying causes. Communicable diseases and maternal, prenatal and nutrition conditions include infectious and parasitic diseases, respiratory infections, and nutritional deficiencies such as underweight and stunting.
SH.DTH.COMM.ZS-gq.name: Cause of death, by communicable diseases and maternal, prenatal and nutrition conditions
SH.DTH.COMM.ZS-gq.source: Derived based on the data from Global Health Estimates 2020: Deaths by Cause, Age, Sex, by Country and by Region, 2000-2019. Geneva, World Health Organization; 2020. Link: https://www.who.int/data/gho/data/themes/mortality-and-global-health-estimates/ghe-leading-causes-of-death

SH.DTH.INJR.ZS-gq.def: Cause of death refers to the share of all deaths for all ages by underlying causes. Injuries include unintentional and intentional injuries.
SH.DTH.INJR.ZS-gq.name: Cause of death
SH.DTH.INJR.ZS-gq.source: Derived based on the data from Global Health Estimates 2020: Deaths by Cause, Age, Sex, by Country and by Region, 2000-2019. Geneva, World Health Organization; 2020. Link: https://www.who.int/data/gho/data/themes/mortality-and-global-health-estimates/ghe-leading-causes-of-death

SH.DTH.NCOM.ZS-gq.def: Cause of death refers to the share of all deaths for all ages by underlying causes. Non-communicable diseases include cancer, diabetes mellitus, cardiovascular diseases, digestive diseases, skin diseases, musculoskeletal diseases, and congenital anomalies.
SH.DTH.NCOM.ZS-gq.name: Cause of death
SH.DTH.NCOM.ZS-gq.source: Derived based on the data from Global Health Estimates 2020: Deaths by Cause, Age, Sex, by Country and by Region, 2000-2019. Geneva, World Health Organization; 2020. Link: https://www.who.int/data/gho/data/themes/mortality-and-global-health-estimates/ghe-leading-causes-of-death

SH.DYN.AIDS.FE.ZS-gq.def: Prevalence of HIV is the percentage of people who are infected with HIV. Female rate is as a percentage of the total population ages 15+ who are living with HIV.
SH.DYN.AIDS.FE.ZS-gq.name: Women's share of population ages 15+ living with HIV

SH.DYN.AIDS.ZS-gq.def: Prevalence of HIV refers to the percentage of people ages 15-49 who are infected with HIV.
SH.DYN.AIDS.ZS-gq.name: Prevalence of HIV

SH.HIV.0014-gq.def: Children living with HIV refers to the number of children ages 0-14 who are infected with HIV.
SH.HIV.0014-gq.name: Children

SH.HIV.1524.FE.ZS-gq.def: Prevalence of HIV, female is the percentage of females who are infected with HIV. Youth rates are as a percentage of the relevant age group.
SH.HIV.1524.FE.ZS-gq.name: Prevalence of HIV

SH.HIV.1524.MA.ZS-gq.def: Prevalence of HIV, male is the percentage of males who are infected with HIV. Youth rates are as a percentage of the relevant age group.
SH.HIV.1524.MA.ZS-gq.name: Prevalence of HIV

SH.HIV.ARTC.ZS-gq.def: Antiretroviral therapy coverage indicates the percentage of all people living with HIV who are receiving antiretroviral therapy.
SH.HIV.ARTC.ZS-gq.name: Antiretroviral therapy coverage

SH.HIV.INCD-gq.def: Number of adults (ages 15-49) newly infected with HIV.
SH.HIV.INCD-gq.name: Adults

SH.HIV.INCD.14-gq.def: Number of children (ages 0-14) newly infected with HIV.
SH.HIV.INCD.14-gq.name: Children

SH.HIV.INCD.TL-gq.def: Number of adults (ages 15+) and children (ages 0-14) newly infected with HIV.
SH.HIV.INCD.TL-gq.name: Adults

SH.HIV.INCD.TL.P3-gq.def: Number of new HIV infections among uninfected populations expressed per 1,000 uninfected population in the year before the period.
SH.HIV.INCD.TL.P3-gq.name: Incidence of HIV

SH.HIV.INCD.YG-gq.def: Number of young people (ages 15-24) newly infected with HIV.
SH.HIV.INCD.YG-gq.name: Young people

SH.HIV.INCD.YG.P3-gq.def: Number of new HIV infections among uninfected populations ages 15-24 expressed per 1,000 uninfected population ages 15-24 in the year before the period.
SH.HIV.INCD.YG.P3-gq.name: Incidence of HIV

SH.HIV.INCD.ZS-gq.def: Number of new HIV infections among uninfected populations ages 15-49 expressed per 1,000 uninfected population in the year before the period.
SH.HIV.INCD.ZS-gq.name: Incidence of HIV

SH.HIV.PMTC.ZS-gq.def: Percentage of pregnant women with HIV who receive antiretroviral medicine for prevention of mother-to-child transmission (PMTCT).
SH.HIV.PMTC.ZS-gq.name: Antiretroviral therapy coverage for PMTCT
SH.HIV.PMTC.ZS-gq.units: % of pregnant women living with HIV

SH.MLR.INCD.P3-gq.def: Incidence of malaria is the number of new cases of malaria in a year per 1,000 population at risk.
SH.MLR.INCD.P3-gq.name: Incidence of malaria
SH.MLR.INCD.P3-gq.source: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository/World Health Statistics (http://apps.who.int/ghodata/).

SH.PRV.SMOK-gq.def: The percentage of the population ages 15 years and over who currently use any tobacco product (smoked and/or smokeless tobacco) on a daily or non-daily basis. Tobacco products include cigarettes, pipes, cigars, cigarillos, waterpipes (hookah, shisha), bidis, kretek, heated tobacco products, and all forms of smokeless (oral and nasal) tobacco. Tobacco products exclude e-cigarettes (which do not contain tobacco), “e-cigars”, “e-hookahs”, JUUL and “e-pipes”. The rates are age-standardized to the WHO Standard Population.
SH.PRV.SMOK-gq.name: Prevalence of current tobacco use
SH.PRV.SMOK-gq.source: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository (http://apps.who.int/ghodata/).

SH.PRV.SMOK.FE-gq.def: The percentage of the female population ages 15 years and over who currently use any tobacco product (smoked and/or smokeless tobacco) on a daily or non-daily basis. Tobacco products include cigarettes, pipes, cigars, cigarillos, waterpipes (hookah, shisha), bidis, kretek, heated tobacco products, and all forms of smokeless (oral and nasal) tobacco. Tobacco products exclude e-cigarettes (which do not contain tobacco), “e-cigars”, “e-hookahs”, JUUL and “e-pipes”. The rates are age-standardized to the WHO Standard Population.
SH.PRV.SMOK.FE-gq.name: Prevalence of current tobacco use
SH.PRV.SMOK.FE-gq.source: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository (http://apps.who.int/ghodata/).

SH.PRV.SMOK.MA-gq.def: The percentage of the male population ages 15 years and over who currently use any tobacco product (smoked and/or smokeless tobacco) on a daily or non-daily basis. Tobacco products include cigarettes, pipes, cigars, cigarillos, waterpipes (hookah, shisha), bidis, kretek, heated tobacco products, and all forms of smokeless (oral and nasal) tobacco. Tobacco products exclude e-cigarettes (which do not contain tobacco), “e-cigars”, “e-hookahs”, JUUL and “e-pipes”. The rates are age-standardized to the WHO Standard Population.
SH.PRV.SMOK.MA-gq.name: Prevalence of current tobacco use
SH.PRV.SMOK.MA-gq.source: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository (http://apps.who.int/ghodata/).

SH.SGR.CRSK.ZS-gq.def: The proportion of population at risk of catastrophic expenditure when surgical care is required. Catastrophic expenditure is defined as direct out of pocket payments for surgical and anaesthesia care exceeding 10% of total income.
SH.SGR.CRSK.ZS-gq.name: Risk of catastrophic expenditure for surgical care
SH.SGR.CRSK.ZS-gq.source: The Program in Global Surgery and Social Change (PGSSC) at Harvard Medical School (https://www.pgssc.org/)

SH.SGR.IRSK.ZS-gq.def: The proportion of population at risk of impoverishing expenditure when surgical care is required. Impoverishing expenditure is defined as direct out of pocket payments for surgical and anaesthesia care which drive people below a poverty threshold (using a threshold of $1.90 PPP/day).
SH.SGR.IRSK.ZS-gq.name: Risk of impoverishing expenditure for surgical care
SH.SGR.IRSK.ZS-gq.source: The Program in Global Surgery and Social Change (PGSSC) at Harvard Medical School (https://www.pgssc.org/)

SH.STA.DIAB.ZS-gq.def: Diabetes prevalence refers to the percentage of people ages 20-79 who have type 1 or type 2 diabetes. It is calculated by adjusting to a standard population age-structure.
SH.STA.DIAB.ZS-gq.name: Diabetes prevalence

SH.STA.FGMS.ZS-gq.def: Percentage of women aged 15–49 who have gone through partial or total removal of the female external genitalia or other injury to the female genital organs for cultural or other non-therapeutic reasons.
SH.STA.FGMS.ZS-gq.name: Female genital mutilation prevalence
SH.STA.FGMS.ZS-gq.source: Demographic and Health Surveys (DHS), Multiple Indicator Cluster Surveys (MICS), and other surveys: STATcompiler (http://www.statcompiler.com/) as of Auguest 28, 2020, UNICEF DATA (http://www.data.unicef.org/) as of August 30, 2020.

SH.STA.ODFC.RU.ZS-gq.def: People practicing open defecation refers to the percentage of the population defecating in the open, such as in fields, forest, bushes, open bodies of water, on beaches, in other open spaces or disposed of with solid waste.
SH.STA.ODFC.RU.ZS-gq.name: People practicing open defecation
SH.STA.ODFC.RU.ZS-gq.source: WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply and Sanitation (http://www.wssinfo.org/).

SH.STA.ODFC.UR.ZS-gq.def: People practicing open defecation refers to the percentage of the population defecating in the open, such as in fields, forest, bushes, open bodies of water, on beaches, in other open spaces or disposed of with solid waste.
SH.STA.ODFC.UR.ZS-gq.name: People practicing open defecation
SH.STA.ODFC.UR.ZS-gq.source: WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply and Sanitation (http://www.wssinfo.org/).

SH.STA.ODFC.ZS-gq.def: People practicing open defecation refers to the percentage of the population defecating in the open, such as in fields, forest, bushes, open bodies of water, on beaches, in other open spaces or disposed of with solid waste.
SH.STA.ODFC.ZS-gq.name: People practicing open defecation
SH.STA.ODFC.ZS-gq.source: WHO/UNICEF Joint Monitoring Programme (JMP) for Water Supply and Sanitation (http://www.wssinfo.org/).

SH.TBS.INCD-gq.def: Incidence of tuberculosis is the estimated number of new and relapse tuberculosis cases arising in a given year, expressed as the rate per 100,000 population. All forms of TB are included, including cases in people living with HIV. Estimates for all years are recalculated as new information becomes available and techniques are refined, so they may differ from those published previously.
SH.TBS.INCD-gq.name: Incidence of tuberculosis
SH.TBS.INCD-gq.source: World Health Organization, Global Tuberculosis Report.
